# O1 Check — Performance & Complexity Rule

Before returning non-trivial TypeScript or Rust code, evaluate **production performance risk**
as if running an o1-check against the change.

## Evaluate before returning code

- Cyclomatic complexity, nesting depth, and function length
- Nested loops over library lists or filesystem entries
- SQLite / Tauri invoke calls inside loops
- Unbounded queries (missing `LIMIT` / pagination on large libraries)
- Sequential awaits that could be batched with `Promise.all`
- O(n²) lookups where a `Map` / `Set` would be O(n)
- Reading entire artwork blobs when only metadata is needed

## Avoid in production paths

- Tauri `invoke` inside tight loops (batch on the Rust side instead)
- Loading all games + decoding Base64 artwork when rendering a list thumbnail grid
- Full directory walks without early exit or depth limits
- Offset pagination for large libraries when cursor/keyset pagination is viable
- Deeply nested loops with `.includes()` / `.find()` on arrays
- Blocking the UI thread with synchronous heavy work in React render paths

## Prefer

- Batch Rust commands (single round-trip for list + metadata)
- Pagination with enforced max page size on library endpoints
- `Map` / `Set` pre-indexing before iteration
- `Promise.all` (with concurrency limits when needed) for independent async work
- Early returns to flatten nesting
- SQLite indexes and parameterized queries in `database/repository.rs`

## When returning non-trivial code

Include a **short complexity note** (e.g. "O(n) single query + O(n) in-memory map build").

If estimated risk is **high** or **critical**, refactor before returning the code.
